<DOC><DOCNO> AP900618-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-90 0733EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-18 0824</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0866</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Retail prices rose a modest 0.2 percent inMay, easing the strain on consumers' budgets after a painful spurtin prices early in the year, the government said.   The April and May moderation in the Labor Department's ConsumerPrice Index curbed inflation for the first five months of the yearto a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.8 percent.   That's up significantly from the 4.6 percent rate for all oflast year, but down sharply from the worrisome 8.5 percent rate inthe first quarter. The latest figures were released Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Industrial production jumped 0.6 percent inMay, but analysts said the sharp gain was due mainly to a temporarybuildup in automobile inventories.   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported Friday that exportshelped shrink the U.S. trade deficit so far this year to an annualrate of $92.16 billion, compared to a deficit for all of 1989 of$108.99 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Donald Trump has missed a payment on junk bondsused to finance one of his Atlantic City resorts, the harshestsignal yet of the troubles plaguing his tottering real estateempire.   Trump has a 10-day grace period from Friday to make the paymentof an estimated $31 million in interest and principal on bonds usedto finance his Trump Castle hotel-casino.   But the failure to meet Friday's deadline nevertheless broughthim a step closer to default, which theoretically could force abankruptcy filing to defend the flamboyant developer fromcollateral-seeking creditors.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Martin A. Siegel, who allegedly took suitcasesof cash from Ivan Boesky in exchange for inside information, hasbeen sentenced to two months in prison.   U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward on Friday cited Siegel'scontrition and cooperation with prosecutors in giving him one ofthe shortest prison terms meted out in Wall Street's insidertrading scandals.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   British stock market experts said they werepuzzled by the New York Stock Exchange's plan to begin after-hourstrading to an effort to recapture trading of U.S. stocks nowconducted overseas.   The experts said Friday such trading is relatively small inEurope, and it also is not clear that the business will grow muchin coming years.   NYSE Chairman John J. Phelan Jr. on Thursday unveiled afive-step plan to trade securities after the exchange's traditionaldaytime hours. The plan would culminate in 24-hour trading by theend of the decade.</TEXT><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Top Soviet leaders say they have won legislativesupport for a market economy, despite rejection of an immediateprice increase for bread and demands for a more detailed blueprintof the transition.   Yuri D. Maslyukov, the chairman of the State PlanningCommission, told reporters Friday that the Supreme Sovietlegislature was right to posptone the first phase of a bread priceincrease Ryzhkov proposed for July 1.   Bread is the staple of the Soviet diet.</TEXT><DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Iran has agreed to pay Amoco Corp.$600 million for facilities seized during the 1979 Islamicrevolution, removing one of the biggest obstacles to renewed tradewith the United States.   Two claims totaling $600 million were awarded to the Americanoil giant, an official of the Iran-United States Claims Tribunalsaid Friday. It was the biggest settlement in the arbitrationbody's nine-year history.</TEXT><DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The world's two largest goldproducing companies say they plan to curtail their miningoperations due to the plummeting price of gold.   Anglo American Corp. of South Africa Ltd. said Friday that twoof its mining companies, Free State State Consolidated Gold MinesLtd. (Freegold) and Vaal Reefs Exploration and Mining Co. Ltd.,would cut back on operations in moves that will cut at least 7,800jobs.   The price of gold reached a 4-year low of $346.25 per ounce inNew York and London before recovering on Thursday. Gold is SouthAfrica's major industry, earning more than half the country'sforeign currency.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   House Democrats have attacked savings and loanbailout agency officials for hiring high-paid consultants, keepingexecutives of failed thrifts on the job and continuing to payothers who perform no work.   Congress is hearing growing reports of overpaid individualsrunning government-held institutions, and of officers from failedinstitutions staying on the government payroll with six-figuresalaries, said Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., chairman of the House Sandamp;Lbailout task force.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Dow Jones industrial average churned ahead to a new closinghigh Friday, in what was otherwise a mixed session for stocks. Theaverage of 30 industrials rose 7.67 points to 2,935.89, surpassingits previous closing peak of 2,935.19 reached on June 4.   Bond prices tumbled on discouraging economic reports.   Gold prices advanced, while the dollar lost ground.   Gold and silver futures rebounded slightly. Livestock and energyfutures were mixed; and grains and soybeans fell.</TEXT></DOC>